  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Pulpit Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_sub_title",
        "text": "Verse 3.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " - ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "Iron...  the joinings; and brass",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". The very first Bible mention of metals (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Genesis 4:22",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") places these two together. Whence Solomon got his \"abundance\" of the latter we have read in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Chronicles 18:8",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; for the \"abundance' of the former he would not necessarily go further than his own land. Although the expression, \"the land whose stones are iron\" (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Deuteronomy 8:9",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), is possibly enough a poetical figure where it stands, yet some of the force of the figure may have sprung from its nearness to ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "fact.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " The abundant use of iron in a great variety of tools, implements, weapons, and the knowledge of it in bar and sheet, might be illustrated from a large number of quotations from Scripture (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Deuteronomy 19:5",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Deuteronomy 27:5",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Samuel 12:31",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Kings 6:5",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Isaiah 10:34",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Amos 1:3",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; and many others). The \"joinings\" were the clamps and plates of various size and shape, which held strongly together, whether beams of wood or blocks of stone. 1 Chronicles 22:3",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
